WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:01.004 --> 00:00:02.046
[♪ dramatic music playing]

2
00:00:02.130 --> 00:00:05.550
Lester likened all the tenants to birds.
his favorite hobby.

3
00:00:05.633 --> 00:00:08.511
And you were the cuckoo chick!

4
00:00:08.594 --> 00:00:10.680
The neediest bird of all. a taker.

5
00:00:10.763 --> 00:00:11.848
The taker?

6
00:00:11.931 --> 00:00:13.558
Mabel. what's the first word
that comes to mind

7
00:00:13.641 --> 00:00:14.726
when you think of me?

8
00:00:14.809 --> 00:00:17.478
-[Mabel Mora] Oh. narcissist.
-What the hell?

9
00:00:17.562 --> 00:00:18.646
Oh. my God.

10
00:00:20.023 --> 00:00:21.107
Mabel Mora?

11
00:00:21.190 --> 00:00:22.442
Althea?

12
00:00:22.525 --> 00:00:25.194
Actually. it's THĒ now.
I shortened it. T-H-Ē.

13
00:00:25.278 --> 00:00:26.571
[Oliver grunting and panting]

14
00:00:26.654 --> 00:00:28.156
Something's not adding up.

15
00:00:28.239 --> 00:00:30.491
Well. I guess it wouldn't hurt
to take a little peek.

16
00:00:30.575 --> 00:00:31.743
We're doing an autopsy?

17
00:00:31.826 --> 00:00:34.245
A meat cleaver to the chest.
Maybe cocaine?

18
00:00:34.328 --> 00:00:36.080
I got it!
Money amounts.

19
00:00:36.164 --> 00:00:37.749
"Brown-headed cowbird."

20
00:00:37.832 --> 00:00:39.542
Maybe these are code names.

21
00:00:39.625 --> 00:00:42.670
There might be a game tonight.
We have to go.

22
00:00:42.754 --> 00:00:45.381
Lester and Nicky
have both been here.

23
00:00:45.465 --> 00:00:46.674
-[keypad beeping]
-[door unlocks]

24
00:00:46.758 --> 00:00:48.593
-[Charles gasps]
-[Oliver grunting]

25
00:00:48.676 --> 00:00:51.554
[Oliver Putnam] You're gonna get us killed
by a bunch of murderous mobsters.

26
00:00:51.637 --> 00:00:53.473
They're all billionaires.

27
00:00:53.556 --> 00:00:56.809
This isn't the mob.
This is the <i>new </i>mob of New York.

28
00:00:56.893 --> 00:00:57.894
[fingers tapping]

29
00:01:00.021 --> 00:01:01.898
[♪ intriguing music playing]

30
00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:06.277
[Camila White]<i> How does it feel</i>
<i>to be worth a billion dollars?</i>

31
00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:09.155
If I'm honest. not as good as it felt

32
00:01:09.238 --> 00:01:13.785
to win my first hundred dollars
on a perfect bluff.

33
00:01:13.868 --> 00:01:18.081
That was the day I fell in love
with parlor games.

34
00:01:18.164 --> 00:01:19.457
and with winning.

35
00:01:21.250 --> 00:01:24.587
I was five years old when
I first beat my father at chess.

36
00:01:25.588 --> 00:01:28.883
Before that. I thought he was
the smartest person in the world.

37
00:01:28.966 --> 00:01:33.346
Broke my heart to learn that <i>I </i>was.

38
00:01:33.429 --> 00:01:36.140
that no one would beat me
for the rest of my life.

39
00:01:37.141 --> 00:01:38.392
What fun is that?

40
00:01:39.393 --> 00:01:42.021
<i>The problem for most rich people</i>
<i>is that there's no amount of money</i>

41
00:01:42.105 --> 00:01:43.648
<i>that can make 'em stop wanting more.</i>

42
00:01:43.731 --> 00:01:46.484
<i>Money's a game.</i>
<i>and they love to win.</i>

43
00:01:46.567 --> 00:01:49.529
<i>I know people see me as a rich guy.</i>
<i>but I barely even think about money.</i>

44
00:01:49.612 --> 00:01:51.030
<i>which is why I'm so normal.</i>

45
00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:53.908
-[phone chiming]
-Alright. good.

46
00:01:53.991 --> 00:01:56.202
Take that. Throw the ball.

47
00:01:56.285 --> 00:01:57.662
-[dog barking]
-[guard] Go get it.

48
00:01:58.037 --> 00:01:59.038
[barking]

49
00:01:59.122 --> 00:02:00.873
It's great getting out with the pup.

50
00:02:00.957 --> 00:02:02.959
-[dog barking]
-He can't find it. Go get it.

51
00:02:03.042 --> 00:02:05.044
[barking continues]

52
00:02:06.254 --> 00:02:08.256
[ambient city street noise]

53
00:02:08.756 --> 00:02:11.759
[♪ light mysterious music playing]

54
00:02:14.887 --> 00:02:17.306
[sighs] Not a typical Saturday night.

55
00:02:17.390 --> 00:02:20.393
I think our days of typical nights here
are behind us.

56
00:02:20.476 --> 00:02:21.561
Let's be fast about this.

57
00:02:21.644 --> 00:02:23.229
-Are we going to talk about--
-[glass clanking]

58
00:02:24.939 --> 00:02:27.108
-What was that?
-[Sebastian "Bash" Steed] Maybe a rat?

59
00:02:27.191 --> 00:02:28.442
[poker chips rattling]

60
00:02:28.526 --> 00:02:30.444
[chips clacking]

61
00:02:30.528 --> 00:02:33.072
[♪ tense suspenseful music playing]

62
00:02:34.949 --> 00:02:36.159
Who's in here?

63
00:02:36.242 --> 00:02:39.495
[♪ suspenseful music continues]

64
00:02:40.955 --> 00:02:42.248
[door closes]

65
00:02:44.792 --> 00:02:47.086
Why are the richest people in the world
in our basement?

66
00:02:47.170 --> 00:02:49.046
And did they kill our doorman?

67
00:02:49.130 --> 00:02:50.464
-[phone dings]
-Find out next season on--

68
00:02:50.548 --> 00:02:52.550
Oh. I'm taking a panorama.

69
00:02:52.633 --> 00:02:55.636
[♪ suspenseful music
continues playing]

70
00:02:55.928 --> 00:02:57.930
[secret closet door rattling shut]

71
00:03:00.391 --> 00:03:03.394
[♪ lively theme song playing]

72
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.074
Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-

73
00:03:44.268 --> 00:03:45.353
[♪ theme song concludes]

74
00:03:46.437 --> 00:03:48.105
-[♪ light mysterious music playing]
-[door opens]

75
00:03:48.189 --> 00:03:50.441
[birds twittering]

76
00:03:51.651 --> 00:03:54.612
Jay Pflug has a bandaged nub.
and we have a finger.

77
00:03:54.695 --> 00:03:58.491
I don't think it's a huge leap to assume
that our finger goes on his nub.

78
00:03:58.574 --> 00:04:01.786
Oh. he's definitely a suspect.
At the least. he was involved.

79
00:04:01.869 --> 00:04:04.038
Maybe the cleaver
that was in Nicky's chest

80
00:04:04.121 --> 00:04:05.539
also chopped off Jay's finger.

81
00:04:05.623 --> 00:04:07.291
And Lester was down there.
Maybe he saw something

82
00:04:07.375 --> 00:04:08.834
-he shouldn't have.
-[robot] <i>Hello.</i>

83
00:04:09.543 --> 00:04:10.544
[electronic beeping]

84
00:04:10.628 --> 00:04:11.837
What the hell?

85
00:04:11.921 --> 00:04:13.339
<i>I'm LESTR.</i>

86
00:04:13.422 --> 00:04:16.467
Aw. look how moved everyone is.

87
00:04:16.550 --> 00:04:18.219
Meet our new doorman.
We named him

88
00:04:18.302 --> 00:04:20.096
after the dead one. in tribute.

89
00:04:20.179 --> 00:04:22.431
L-E-S-T-R.

90
00:04:22.515 --> 00:04:26.143
Logic Engineered Secure Tenant Robot.

91
00:04:26.227 --> 00:04:27.979
Those words don't even
make sense together.

92
00:04:28.062 --> 00:04:30.231
They're trying to trick us
into thinking it's a tribute

93
00:04:30.314 --> 00:04:33.025
-instead of the rise of the machine.
-[LESTR robot]<i> That's true.</i>

94
00:04:33.109 --> 00:04:36.320
<i>My greatest challenge</i>
<i>is my unsettling effect on humans.</i>

95
00:04:36.404 --> 00:04:39.573
Well. I've seen <i>The Terminator.</i>
so I'm on Team Machine.

96
00:04:39.657 --> 00:04:43.160
As the keeper of the building's secrets.
the board hired me to train LESTR.

97
00:04:43.244 --> 00:04:46.247
This is so sad.
A robot doorman.

98
00:04:46.330 --> 00:04:48.666
The beginning of the end
of old New York.

99
00:04:48.749 --> 00:04:50.293
-No!
-[pen clatters]

100
00:04:50.376 --> 00:04:54.922
See. the machine will just handle things
like deliveries or reminders.

101
00:04:55.006 --> 00:04:57.008
Thanks to the union--
my union--

102
00:04:57.091 --> 00:04:59.385
there will always be
a human face at the door.

103
00:04:59.468 --> 00:05:02.430
Just. hopefully this human.

104
00:05:02.513 --> 00:05:05.141
He's right.
We couldn't get rid of him.

105
00:05:05.224 --> 00:05:08.853
[LESTR robot] <i>I just need to scan</i>
<i>everyone's iris and fingerprint.</i>

106
00:05:08.936 --> 00:05:11.772
That thing's not getting
anywhere near my irises.

107
00:05:11.856 --> 00:05:14.442
-[electronic whirring]
-Alright. I'm gonna get my hair done.

108
00:05:14.525 --> 00:05:17.111
God knows why.
since nobody ever notices.

109
00:05:18.988 --> 00:05:22.992
What's happening
to our sweet little murder building?

110
00:05:24.243 --> 00:05:26.579
Yeah. Things are changing fast.

111
00:05:27.955 --> 00:05:28.956
[shoes squeaking]

112
00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:31.542
-Are you doing toe raises?
-Yeah. I do toe raises.

113
00:05:31.625 --> 00:05:33.210
I've never seen you do a toe raise.

114
00:05:33.294 --> 00:05:35.671
Have you ever seen me brush my teeth?
I do that too.

115
00:05:35.755 --> 00:05:37.256
[elevator dings]

116
00:05:37.340 --> 00:05:39.550
[♪ light plucky music playing]

117
00:05:40.468 --> 00:05:41.761
[Mabel sighs]

118
00:05:43.971 --> 00:05:45.973
I took Winnie's doggy Ritalin.
stayed up all night.

119
00:05:46.057 --> 00:05:49.143
-and basically solved this.
-You two are a lot for me today.

120
00:05:49.226 --> 00:05:50.644
-Vince.
-What are you doing here?

121
00:05:50.728 --> 00:05:52.605
And look at you with two eyes.

122
00:05:52.688 --> 00:05:55.775
Hiya. guys.
Lester and I were birding buddies.

123
00:05:55.858 --> 00:05:58.402
So. Oliver invited me
up here to decode the ledger.

124
00:05:58.486 --> 00:06:00.571
figure out which one of the birds
was playing cards

125
00:06:00.654 --> 00:06:02.907
-on the night that he died.
-You birded with Lester?

126
00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:04.450
Well. he was the expert.

127
00:06:04.533 --> 00:06:06.410
I just followed along
to keep him honest.

128
00:06:06.494 --> 00:06:10.164
He had a knack for turning
a robin into a bushtit...

129
00:06:10.247 --> 00:06:11.832
[chuckles]
...if you know what I mean.

130
00:06:11.916 --> 00:06:13.459
No one has any idea
what you mean.

131
00:06:13.542 --> 00:06:15.044
Well. he was an optimist.

132
00:06:15.127 --> 00:06:18.047
Very good at life.
but not so at birding.

133
00:06:18.130 --> 00:06:21.258
But I miss him.
I miss our days in the park.

134
00:06:21.342 --> 00:06:22.551
Sit. sit.

135
00:06:23.594 --> 00:06:24.929
Okay.

136
00:06:25.012 --> 00:06:26.472
[gasps dramatically]

137
00:06:26.555 --> 00:06:27.890
[Mabel]
Oh-ho. wow!

138
00:06:27.973 --> 00:06:31.477
An Oliver Putnam murder board.
Love the sari.

139
00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:34.313
Yeah. from my '70s Rajneesh days.

140
00:06:34.397 --> 00:06:36.065
Please let that be a hash stain.

141
00:06:36.148 --> 00:06:39.110
That's a lot of work.
Oliver. what happened to you?

142
00:06:39.193 --> 00:06:41.404
Well. I thought about
what you said to me the other day

143
00:06:41.487 --> 00:06:43.697
when you complimented me.
What'd you call me?

144
00:06:43.781 --> 00:06:46.534
-Self-centered narcissist.
-[Oliver] Yes. that-- that was it.

145
00:06:46.617 --> 00:06:48.536
Anyway. I heard it.

146
00:06:48.619 --> 00:06:52.123
So. last night. as I lay there
thinking about myself...

147
00:06:53.207 --> 00:06:54.875
the strangest thing happened.

148
00:06:54.959 --> 00:06:56.585
I suddenly thought about <i>you</i>

149
00:06:56.669 --> 00:06:59.171
and how you always make
the murder boards.

150
00:06:59.255 --> 00:07:02.591
So. I thought to myself.
I'll do it. for you.

151
00:07:02.675 --> 00:07:04.218
Bravo. Oliver. Bravo.

152
00:07:04.301 --> 00:07:06.137
-What growth.
-Okay.

153
00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:07.721
We did solve one mystery:

154
00:07:07.805 --> 00:07:10.349
why Lester wrote down
the player's names

155
00:07:10.433 --> 00:07:12.476
using a secret bird code.

156
00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:14.186
They're the most powerful
people in the world.

157
00:07:14.270 --> 00:07:16.105
He was scared of them.

158
00:07:16.188 --> 00:07:19.733
Somebody be recordin'.
because I am about to get birdie with it.

159
00:07:19.817 --> 00:07:21.652
-[recorder dings]
-Per Lester's notes.

160
00:07:21.735 --> 00:07:25.698
the gaming parlor usually hosted
a whole flock of birds.

161
00:07:25.781 --> 00:07:27.491
But last Saturday.

162
00:07:27.575 --> 00:07:28.617
there were only five.

163
00:07:28.701 --> 00:07:31.245
Now. first. Nicky.

164
00:07:31.328 --> 00:07:33.372
He is the Brown-headed cowbird.

165
00:07:33.456 --> 00:07:37.668
known for their mafia-like
retaliatory behavior.

166
00:07:37.751 --> 00:07:39.712
[mimics Brown-headed cowbird call]

167
00:07:39.795 --> 00:07:41.422
-[shouting caw]
-Oof! Okay. 'kay. 'kay.

168
00:07:41.505 --> 00:07:42.756
you don't have to do the calls.

169
00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:44.550
Well. it sounds like
a mobster. doesn't it?

170
00:07:44.633 --> 00:07:48.220
Next. Jay Pflug.
heir to the Pflug fortune.

171
00:07:48.304 --> 00:07:51.974
maker of Pflug faucets.
which gave everybody lead poisoning.

172
00:07:52.057 --> 00:07:54.268
So. they founded Pflug Pharma.

173
00:07:54.351 --> 00:07:57.646
which invented a medicine
to cure lead poisoning.

174
00:07:57.730 --> 00:07:59.231
Made billions.

175
00:07:59.315 --> 00:08:02.943
He branded himself
as. uh. this black sheep philanthropist.

176
00:08:03.027 --> 00:08:04.987
but the guy is a monster.

177
00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:08.282
His last nonprofit funneled money
to guerrilla groups.

178
00:08:08.365 --> 00:08:10.201
The terrorists. not the primates.

179
00:08:10.284 --> 00:08:11.619
L-Let's-- let's keep it on birds.

180
00:08:11.702 --> 00:08:14.038
He's the Eurasian Jay.

181
00:08:14.121 --> 00:08:15.247
[mimics Eurasian jay call]

182
00:08:15.331 --> 00:08:17.958
-[Charles and Vince mimicking loudly]
-[both laughing]

183
00:08:18.042 --> 00:08:19.168
I. too. get my bird on.

184
00:08:19.251 --> 00:08:21.879
Okay. lotta new colors on you.

185
00:08:21.962 --> 00:08:26.759
Anyway. since the Jay bird
is missing a claw...

186
00:08:26.842 --> 00:08:28.802
No. I'm sorry. I'm done.

187
00:08:28.886 --> 00:08:30.763
He's missing a finger.
so. it's obviously--

188
00:08:30.846 --> 00:08:32.973
No. no. no.
We're not done.

189
00:08:33.057 --> 00:08:34.183
Bash Steed.

190
00:08:34.934 --> 00:08:37.311
AI genius. longevity freak.

191
00:08:37.394 --> 00:08:39.939
Way older than he looks.
but no one knows how old

192
00:08:40.022 --> 00:08:41.315
because he owns the internet.

193
00:08:41.398 --> 00:08:43.359
Now. I <i>have </i>to find out
how old he is.

194
00:08:43.442 --> 00:08:45.653
He is the kākāpō.

195
00:08:45.736 --> 00:08:48.030
[mimics kākāpō gulping call]

196
00:08:48.113 --> 00:08:51.700
They are known to live up
to 90 years in the wild.

197
00:08:51.784 --> 00:08:54.119
And finally. Camila White.

198
00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:57.498
Lifestyle queen. hotel magnate.

199
00:08:57.581 --> 00:08:59.375
duchess of cashmere.

200
00:08:59.458 --> 00:09:02.586
You can buy a candle
that smells like the inside of her nose.

201
00:09:02.670 --> 00:09:04.964
She is the queen of decor.

202
00:09:05.047 --> 00:09:08.801
The bowerbird.
maker of beautiful nests.

203
00:09:08.884 --> 00:09:11.554
[Vince and Charles
mimicking bowerbird call]

204
00:09:11.637 --> 00:09:12.680
[screeching] Ah!

205
00:09:12.763 --> 00:09:17.518
Okay. anyways.
there's a finger in Charles's freezer

206
00:09:17.601 --> 00:09:19.728
and we have a suspect
missing a finger.

207
00:09:19.812 --> 00:09:22.940
So. how do we get to Jay?

208
00:09:24.066 --> 00:09:25.192
[Oliver sighs]

209
00:09:25.276 --> 00:09:28.070
-We let him know we're onto him.
-[Oliver] Ahh.

210
00:09:28.988 --> 00:09:29.989
Yes.

211
00:09:30.072 --> 00:09:32.491
[Oliver] [on computer] <i>And while we here</i>
<i>at </i>Only Murders in the Building

212
00:09:32.575 --> 00:09:34.952
<i>-aren't pointing fingers just yet...</i>
-[♪ podcast theme music playing]

213
00:09:35.035 --> 00:09:39.123
<i>...we're wading into the dangerous waters</i>
<i>of both old mob and new.</i>

214
00:09:39.206 --> 00:09:40.791
[Charles-Haden Savage]
<i>Uber rich powerbrokers</i>

215
00:09:40.874 --> 00:09:42.876
<i>who don't have to break an arm</i>
<i>to get what they want.</i>

216
00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:44.461
<i>They just write a check.</i>

217
00:09:44.545 --> 00:09:46.088
[Mabel]
<i>No one writes checks anymore.</i>

218
00:09:46.171 --> 00:09:49.592
[Charles] <i>We already have some ideas</i>
<i>about who has a partial hand</i>

219
00:09:49.675 --> 00:09:52.720
<i>in these two deaths.</i>
<i>so don't miss season five.</i>

220
00:09:52.803 --> 00:09:54.096
This is so good.

221
00:09:54.179 --> 00:09:55.681
Oh. we're definitely
gonna hear from him.

222
00:09:55.764 --> 00:09:57.141
He'll wanna defend himself.

223
00:09:57.224 --> 00:09:58.851
-Post. young one!
-[computer key clicks]

224
00:09:58.934 --> 00:10:01.228
I do wish we'd worked
in the word "phalange."

225
00:10:01.312 --> 00:10:05.107
Okay. for the last time. Charles.
phalange-thropist is not a good pun.

226
00:10:05.190 --> 00:10:06.483
-That's funny.
-[Oliver sighs]

227
00:10:06.567 --> 00:10:08.652
-To you.
-[Oliver] Mm.

228
00:10:10.487 --> 00:10:12.489
[birds cawing. wings fluttering]

229
00:10:15.034 --> 00:10:16.744
[elevator dings]

230
00:10:16.827 --> 00:10:18.078
Oh. my God. hi!

231
00:10:18.162 --> 00:10:19.872
Althea-- THĒ.

232
00:10:19.955 --> 00:10:21.498
Um. this is Oliver.

233
00:10:21.582 --> 00:10:24.918
-Oh. hello. How are you?
-Hi. Cute pillows.

234
00:10:25.002 --> 00:10:27.671
Yes. I'm bequeathing them to young Mabel
for her new apartment.

235
00:10:27.755 --> 00:10:29.840
That is so kind of you.

236
00:10:29.923 --> 00:10:34.762
I mean. I could buy myself pillows.
it's just. these are vintage Missoni.

237
00:10:34.845 --> 00:10:36.972
THĒ! Hi!

